<paragraph id="8BD81E35A471FF96FF66EE70F684F901" blockId="21.[151,1437,1547,2005]" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="B913C227A471FF96FF66EE70F34EF9FD" bold="true" box="[199,356,1619,1645]" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Morphology:</emphasis>
Colour is beige after fixation. The 
<typeStatus id="54DCA097A471FF96FCA0EE70F149F9FD" box="[769,867,1619,1645]" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">holotype</typeStatus>
is a tubular fragment (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A471FF96FBCEEE70F6F0F9FD" box="[1135,1242,1619,1645]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetId="figure-23@22.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Holotype in ethanol. B—General view of a skeletal section. C—A triactine (arrow) at the cortical region. D—Giant tetractines organised at the skeleton. E—Apical of the tetractines (arrows) perforating the atrial wall and layer of diactines surrounding the atrium. F—Subatrial/ atrial region composed exclusively of diactines (arrow). Abbreviations: at—Atrium and ct—cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642315/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Fig. 12A</figureCitation>
), and a fringe of trichoxeas was present, according to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF663C4A471FF96FD94EE54F0FDF901" author="Burton, M." box="[565,727,1655,1681]" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" pagination="237 - 392" refId="ref16157" refString="Burton, M. (1932) Sponges. Discovery Reports, 6, 237 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 24379" type="journal article" year="1932">Burton (1932)</bibRefCitation>
. The type of aquiferous system is unclear.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A471FF96FF66EEB8F672F845" blockId="21.[151,1437,1547,2005]" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis id="B913C227A471FF96FF66EEB8F315F925" bold="true" box="[199,319,1691,1717]" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Anatomy:</emphasis>
The skeleton has no similarity with the other species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A471FF96FC17EEB8F662F925" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[950,1096,1691,1717]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A471FF96FC17EEB8F662F925" box="[950,1096,1691,1717]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The cortical region is formed by triactines of varying sizes and subcortical giant tetractines (which are possibly the only typical character of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A471FF96FF36EEC0F362F96E" authorityName="Dendy" authorityYear="1892" box="[151,328,1763,1790]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Amphoriscidae</taxonomicName>
). However, there is no typical inarticulation (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A471FF96FCF3EEC0F191F96D" box="[850,955,1763,1789]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetId="figure-23@22.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Holotype in ethanol. B—General view of a skeletal section. C—A triactine (arrow) at the cortical region. D—Giant tetractines organised at the skeleton. E—Apical of the tetractines (arrows) perforating the atrial wall and layer of diactines surrounding the atrium. F—Subatrial/ atrial region composed exclusively of diactines (arrow). Abbreviations: at—Atrium and ct—cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642315/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Fig. 12B</figureCitation>
). The presence of several broken spicules makes the visualisation of the triactines difficult (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A471FF96FD19EF24F134F8B1" box="[696,798,1799,1825]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetId="figure-23@22.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Holotype in ethanol. B—General view of a skeletal section. C—A triactine (arrow) at the cortical region. D—Giant tetractines organised at the skeleton. E—Apical of the tetractines (arrows) perforating the atrial wall and layer of diactines surrounding the atrium. F—Subatrial/ atrial region composed exclusively of diactines (arrow). Abbreviations: at—Atrium and ct—cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642315/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Fig. 12C</figureCitation>
). The apical actines of the subcortical tetractines cross the entire choanosome, often perforating the atrium (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A471FF96FD1AEF08F167F8D5" box="[699,845,1835,1861]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetId="figure-23@22.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Holotype in ethanol. B—General view of a skeletal section. C—A triactine (arrow) at the cortical region. D—Giant tetractines organised at the skeleton. E—Apical of the tetractines (arrows) perforating the atrial wall and layer of diactines surrounding the atrium. F—Subatrial/ atrial region composed exclusively of diactines (arrow). Abbreviations: at—Atrium and ct—cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642315/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Figs. 12D, E</figureCitation>
). The subatrial/atrial region is comprised exclusively of large tangential diactines. They are abundant and line the atrial cavity (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A471FF96FC7EEF6CF645F8F9" box="[991,1135,1871,1897]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1616,1640]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetId="figure-23@22.[151,1436,181,1592]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 12. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Holotype in ethanol. B—General view of a skeletal section. C—A triactine (arrow) at the cortical region. D—Giant tetractines organised at the skeleton. E—Apical of the tetractines (arrows) perforating the atrial wall and layer of diactines surrounding the atrium. F—Subatrial/ atrial region composed exclusively of diactines (arrow). Abbreviations: at—Atrium and ct—cortex." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642315/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="60">Figs. 12E, F</figureCitation>
). A specific atrial skeleton comprised of triactines or tetractines is absent. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF663C4A471FF96FC98EF50F1F0F81D" author="Burton, M." box="[825,986,1907,1933]" pageId="21" pageNumber="60" pagination="237 - 392" refId="ref16157" refString="Burton, M. (1932) Sponges. Discovery Reports, 6, 237 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 24379" type="journal article" year="1932">Burton (1932)</bibRefCitation>
, large diactines similar to those found in the inner part of the sponge were found projecting from the cortex, but they were not observed here. The aquiferous system could not be recognised and was not mentioned along the original description.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF184EBDA472FF95FF36EE73F62CF943" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642315" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5642315" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642315/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="61" startId="22.[151,250,1616,1640]" targetBox="[151,1436,181,1592]" targetPageId="22">
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A472FF95FF36EE73F62CF943" blockId="22.[151,1437,1616,1748]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FF36EE73F309F9F8" bold="true" box="[151,291,1616,1640]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">FIGURE 12.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A472FF95FE8CEE73F04DF9F8" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1963" box="[301,615,1616,1640]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="22" pageNumber="61" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FE8CEE73F04DF9F8" box="[301,615,1616,1640]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FC7AEE73F62DF9F8" bold="true" box="[987,1031,1616,1640]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">A—</emphasis>
Holotype in ethanol. 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FB46EE73F73BF9F8" bold="true" box="[1255,1297,1616,1640]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">B—</emphasis>
General view of a skeletal section. 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FED3EE57F3B4F91C" bold="true" box="[370,414,1652,1676]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">C—</emphasis>
A triactine (arrow) at the cortical region. 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FCE6EE57F158F91C" bold="true" box="[839,882,1652,1676]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">D—</emphasis>
Giant tetractines organised at the skeleton. 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FA8FEE57F773F91C" bold="true" box="[1326,1369,1652,1676]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">E—</emphasis>
