</caption>
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A472FF95FF66EF05F31BF8D1" blockId="22.[151,1437,1830,2037]" box="[199,305,1830,1857]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FF66EF05F303F8D0" bold="true" box="[199,297,1830,1856]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">Spicules</emphasis>
:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A472FF95FF66EF69F360F83C" blockId="22.[151,1437,1830,2037]" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">
Cortical triactines: Regular, actines are slightly conical and sharp. The actines are straight (paired actines: 123.1– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FF45EF4DF309F818" box="[228,291,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">150.7</emphasis>
±21.6–204.4/ 8.4– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FE51EF4DF00BF818" box="[496,545,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">12.2</emphasis>
± 1.7–15.3 μm; unpaired actines: 81.5– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FC78EF4DF632F818" box="[985,1048,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">133.6</emphasis>
±23.2–180.0/ 8.9– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FB4DEF4DF701F818" box="[1260,1323,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">122.3</emphasis>
±2.0–18.3 μm) (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A472FF95FF74EFB1F317F83C" box="[213,317,1938,1964]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="23.[151,250,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,309,798]" captionTargetId="figure-69@23.[156,1432,309,804]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 13. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Cortical triactine. B—Subcortical tetractine. C—Subatrial/atrial diactine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642317" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642317/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A472FF94FF66EF95F01AFF45" blockId="22.[151,1437,1830,2037]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1437,150,285]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="62" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">
Subcortical tetractines: Giant, actines are slightly conical to conical and blunt. The paired actines are slightly curved (111.4– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FE9EEFF9F354F864" box="[319,382,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">146.6</emphasis>
±21.8–192.1/ 10.8– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A472FF95FDF8EFF9F0A0F864" box="[601,650,2010,2036]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="61">14.5</emphasis>
± 2.0–19.2 μm). The unpaired actine is curved from the base to the tip (93.9– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF41E8B5F337FF20" box="[224,285,150,176]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">116.7</emphasis>
±21.5–156.6/ 14.1– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FE57E8B4F00DFF21" box="[502,551,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">15.2</emphasis>
±1.1–16.9 μm). The apical actine is long and conical (174.3– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FB69E8B4F72DFF21" box="[1224,1287,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">228.3</emphasis>
±29.1–285.4/ 16.9– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF77E898F32DFF45" box="[214,263,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">20.8</emphasis>
±2.2–26.3 μm) (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A473FF94FE1CE898F00EFF45" box="[445,548,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="23.[151,250,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,309,798]" captionTargetId="figure-69@23.[156,1432,309,804]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 13. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Cortical triactine. B—Subcortical tetractine. C—Subatrial/atrial diactine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642317" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642317/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Fig. 13B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A473FF94FF66E8FCF17EFE8D" blockId="23.[151,1437,150,285]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">
Diactines: Large, sinuous along their length. Most of them have one of the tips blunt while the other is sharp (330.0– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF4FE921F307FE8C" box="[238,301,258,284]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">464.8</emphasis>
±89.6–632.6/ 9.0– 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FE5BE920F001FE8D" box="[506,555,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">18.9</emphasis>
±4.0–25.7 μm) (
<figureCitation id="135C02B0A473FF94FD41E920F16DFE8D" box="[736,839,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="23.[151,250,827,851]" captionTargetBox="[163,1421,309,798]" captionTargetId="figure-69@23.[156,1432,309,804]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 13. Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera (holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). A—Cortical triactine. B—Subcortical tetractine. C—Subatrial/atrial diactine." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642317" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642317/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Fig. 13C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF184EBDA473FF94FF36EB18F39DFCE7" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5642317" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5642317" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5642317/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" startId="23.[151,250,827,851]" targetBox="[163,1421,309,798]" targetPageId="23">
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A473FF94FF36EB18F39DFCE7" blockId="23.[151,1437,827,887]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF36EB18F334FCC3" bold="true" box="[151,286,827,851]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">FIGURE 13.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FE83EB18F07DFCC3" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1963" box="[290,599,827,851]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FE83EB18F07DFCC3" box="[290,599,827,851]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(holotype BMNH 1928.2.15.833). 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FC17EB18F1C8FCC3" bold="true" box="[950,994,827,851]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">A—</emphasis>
Cortical triactine. 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FB37EB18F695FCC3" bold="true" box="[1174,1215,827,851]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">B—</emphasis>
Subcortical tetractine. 
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF36EB7CF2E9FCE7" bold="true" box="[151,195,863,887]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">C—</emphasis>
Subatrial/atrial diactine.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C37D4DBEA473FF9BFF66EB86F739FE19" lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="63" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A473FF94FF66EB86F3AEFAB7" blockId="23.[151,1437,933,2040]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF66EB86F317FC2F" bold="true" box="[199,317,933,959]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species was originally described as 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FC81EB86F665FC2F" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[800,1103,933,959]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FC81EB86F665FC2F" box="[800,1103,933,959]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Leucaltis gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(subclass 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FB68EB86F707FC50" authorityName="Bidder" authorityYear="1898" box="[1225,1325,933,960]" class="Calcarea" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="subClass" subClass="Calcinea">Calcinea</taxonomicName>
) and was later transferred to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FED6EBEAF023FC73" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[375,521,969,995]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FED6EBEAF023FC73" box="[375,521,969,995]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(subclass 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FD24EBEAF12FFC74" authorityName="Bidder" authorityYear="1898" box="[645,773,969,996]" class="Calcarea" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="subClass" subClass="Calcaronea">Calcaronea</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFF663C4A473FF94FCBFEBEAF199FC73" author="Burton, M." box="[798,947,969,995]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" pagination="237 - 392" refId="ref16157" refString="Burton, M. (1932) Sponges. Discovery Reports, 6, 237 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 24379" type="journal article" year="1932">Burton 1932</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF663C4A473FF94FC63EBEAF1D4FC74" author="Burton, M." box="[962,1022,969,996]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" refId="ref16231" refString="Burton, M. (1963) A revision of the Classification of the Calcareous Sponges: with a Catalogue of the specimens in the British Museum. Order of the trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London, 693 pp." type="book" year="1963">1963</bibRefCitation>
). Such a reallocation would, by the standards of modern-day research on 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FD9AEBCEF0B7FB97" authorityName="Bowerbank" authorityYear="1864" box="[571,669,1005,1031]" class="Calcarea" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="class">Calcarea</taxonomicName>
systematics, be considered out of the ordinary and require a detailed explanation, yet at that time Burton did not note the reasons supporting his decision in any detail. In his discussion of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FE8BEC16F06AFBC0" authority=", Burton (1963)" authorityName=", Burton" authorityYear="1963" box="[298,576,1077,1104]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FE8BEC16F3BBFBDF" box="[298,401,1077,1103]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Leucaltis</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF663C4A473FF94FE3EEC15F06AFBC0" author="Burton, M." box="[415,576,1077,1104]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" refId="ref16231" refString="Burton, M. (1963) A revision of the Classification of the Calcareous Sponges: with a Catalogue of the specimens in the British Museum. Order of the trustees of the British Museum (Natural History), London, 693 pp." type="book" year="1963">Burton (1963)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
argued that “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FD7BEC15F19CFBDF" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[730,950,1077,1103]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FD7BEC15F19CFBDF" box="[730,950,1077,1103]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">L. gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is aberrant and is here doubtfully assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FF16EC7AF363FBE3" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[183,329,1113,1139]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF16EC7AF363FBE3" box="[183,329,1113,1139]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, suggesting that the only certainty the author had was that it was not 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FB25EC7AF6C1FBE3" authorityName=", Burton" authorityYear="1963" box="[1156,1259,1113,1139]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FB25EC7AF6C1FBE3" box="[1156,1259,1113,1139]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Leucaltis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He named the species “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FF5DEC5EF3A4FB07" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[252,398,1149,1175]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF5DEC5EF3A4FB07" box="[252,398,1149,1175]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
? 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FE0BEC5EF042FB07" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[426,616,1149,1175]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FE0BEC5EF042FB07" box="[426,616,1149,1175]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, and although we suspect that he was influenced by the presence of the giant cortical tetractines, this cannot be confirmed.Also, there is no information or illustration in the literature about the aquiferous system of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FE19ECE5F0BDFB4F" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[440,663,1221,1248]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FE19ECE5F0BDFB4F" box="[440,663,1221,1248]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">A. gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which would be essential to support its allocation in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FAA2ECE6F7BFFB4F" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[1283,1429,1221,1247]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FAA2ECE6F7BFFB4F" box="[1283,1429,1221,1247]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Whether or not it was one of the characters used by Burton to assign the species in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FBE5ECCAF6FCFA93" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[1092,1238,1257,1283]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FBE5ECCAF6FCFA93" box="[1092,1238,1257,1283]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a question that remains unanswered.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A473FF94FF66ED11F69BF9FC" blockId="23.[151,1437,933,2040]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">
We analysed the 
<typeStatus id="54DCA097A473FF94FE20ED12F3C9FADB" box="[385,483,1329,1355]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">holotype</typeStatus>
(BMNH 1928.2.15.833) in this study. The microscopical slides contain sections of the skeleton that were probably not stained since it was not possible to unequivocally confirm whether 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FB63ED75F7B6FAFF" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[1218,1436,1365,1392]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FB63ED75F7B6FAFF" box="[1218,1436,1365,1392]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">A.gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the syconoid aquiferous system typical of the genus. We observed the main morphological characters reported in the original description, such as the presence of cortical triactines, subcortical giant tetractines with a long apical actine, and diactines. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF663C4A473FF94FE33EDE1F01FFA4B" author="Burton, M." box="[402,565,1473,1500]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" pagination="237 - 392" refId="ref16157" refString="Burton, M. (1932) Sponges. Discovery Reports, 6, 237 - 392. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 24379" type="journal article" year="1932">Burton (1932)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned diactines protruding through the cortex, but we did not observe this characteristic. The absence of a subatrial layer of triactines/tetractines was also confirmed and, consequently, the absence of inarticulate skeletal organisation. Therefore, the most important diagnostic characters typical of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FF36EE0EF303F9D7" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[151,297,1581,1607]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FF36EE0EF303F9D7" box="[151,297,1581,1607]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
either could not be confirmed (the syconoid aquiferous system) or are absent (the inarticulation formed by the apical actines of giant cortical tetractines and the unpaired actine of subatrial spicules).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD81E35A473FF9BFF66EE55F739FE19" blockId="23.[151,1437,933,2040]" lastBlockId="24.[151,1437,151,393]" lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="63" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">
In order to assess the possibility of assigning 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FD73EE55F19AF91F" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[722,944,1653,1680]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FD73EE55F19AF91F" box="[722,944,1653,1680]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">A. gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in another genus, a diagnosis of all genera under the order 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FEF2EEBAF3DCF923" authorityName="Hartman" authorityYear="1958" box="[339,502,1689,1715]" class="Calcarea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="order">Leucosolenida</taxonomicName>
was carried out. The presence of triactines and tetractines and of an atrial layer of diactines is a remarkable character found only in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FD5FEE9EF159F947" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1872" box="[766,883,1725,1751]" class="Calcarea" family="Grantiidae" genus="Sycodorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FD5FEE9EF159F947" box="[766,883,1725,1751]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Sycodorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, although members of this genus are syconoid. Tangential triactines and tetractines also occur along the atrial cavity, suggesting that, even if 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FB1FEEC1F7B6F96B" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[1214,1436,1761,1788]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FB1FEEC1F7B6F96B" box="[1214,1436,1761,1788]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">A. gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is syconoid, it could not be allocated in 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FDFBEF26F0E5F88F" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1872" box="[602,719,1797,1823]" class="Calcarea" family="Grantiidae" genus="Sycodorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FDFBEF26F0E5F88F" box="[602,719,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Sycodorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. An alternative decision would be to propose a new genus. The reasons why we did not choose this option to solve the problem of 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A473FF94FC07EF09F6ACF8D3" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[934,1158,1833,1860]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A473FF94FC07EF09F6ACF8D3" box="[934,1158,1833,1860]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">A. gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were as follows: (i) the 
<typeStatus id="54DCA097A473FF94FF36EF6EF2D3F8F7" box="[151,249,1869,1895]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">holotype</typeStatus>
is tiny, and no reports of additional specimens exist that could enrich our understanding of the morphology of the new genus; (ii) the lack of data on the aquiferous system could raise doubts on the family in which the genus should be inserted and also makes the description of a robust diagnosis difficult; (iii) the species is represented only by the 
<typeStatus id="54DCA097A473FF94FEBEEF9AF3AEF843" box="[287,388,1977,2003]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">holotype</typeStatus>
, found at 
<collectingCountry id="F3705EA5A473FF94FE57EF9AF091F843" box="[502,699,1977,2003]" name="Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha" pageId="23" pageNumber="62">Tristan da Cunha</collectingCountry>
, Southern Atlantic Ocean, at a depth of 
<quantity id="4C9FB3D0A473FF94FB23EF9AF725F844" box="[1154,1295,1977,2004]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" unit="m" value="110.0" valueMax="140.0" valueMin="80.0">
80 to 
<specimenCount id="9D61D5BCA473FF94FB65EF9AF725F844" box="[1220,1295,1977,2004]" pageId="23" pageNumber="62" type="generic">140 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. The lack of perspective in finding fresh samples to elucidate the questions mentioned earlier suggests that the problem with the species would persist (not as 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A47CFF9BFE44E8B4F05DFF21" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[485,631,151,177]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="24" pageNumber="63" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A47CFF9BFE44E8B4F05DFF21" box="[485,631,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="63">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but as a newly named genus); finally, (iv) we cannot undoubtedly rule out 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A47CFF9BFF62E898F38BFF45" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1932" box="[195,417,187,213]" class="Calcarea" family="Leucaltidae" genus="Leucaltis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Clathrinida" pageId="24" pageNumber="63" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A47CFF9BFF62E898F38BFF45" box="[195,417,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="63">A. gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
actually belonging to 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A47CFF9BFD3EE898F11BFF45" authorityName="Haeckel" authorityYear="1870" box="[671,817,187,213]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="24" pageNumber="63" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B913C227A47CFF9BFD3EE898F11BFF45" box="[671,817,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="63">Amphoriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the absence of an inarticulate organisation could be a secondary character caused by the loss of subatrial spicules along the species’ evolutionary history. The latter question will be resolved after the species is tested in phylogenetic analyses, though, as highlighted above, there is no fresh material available. Therefore, we decided to be conservative and avoid potentially increasing the number of open questions on the classification of this species. 
<taxonomicName id="4C6765B6A47CFF9BFD7AE968F619FEF5" authorityName="Burton" authorityYear="1963" box="[731,1075,331,357]" class="Calcarea" family="Amphoriscidae" genus="Amphoriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="24" pageNumber="63" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="gastrorhabdifera">
<emphasis id="B913C227A47CFF9BFD7AE968F619FEF5" box="[731,1075,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="63">Amphoriscus gastrorhabdifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is thus maintained in the genus, but we indicate that it should be considered as 
<emphasis id="B913C227A47CFF9BFD03E94CF117FE19" box="[674,829,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="63">incertae sedis</emphasis>
until the discovery of additional samples.
</paragraph>
